{"id":"2112.05624","submitter":"Valla Fatemi","authors":"V. Fatemi, P. D. Kurilovich, M. Hays, D. Bouman, T. Connolly, S.\n  Diamond, N. E. Frattini, V. D. Kurilovich, P. Krogstrup, J. Nygard, A.\n  Geresdi, L. I. Glazman, M. H. Devoret","title":"Microwave susceptibility observation of interacting many-body Andreev\n  states","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.129.227701","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.mes-hall cond-mat.supr-con","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Electrostatic charging affects the many-body spectrum of Andreev states, yet\nits influence on their microwave properties has not been elucidated. We\ndeveloped a circuit quantum electrodynamics probe that, in addition to\ntransition spectroscopy, measures the microwave susceptibility of different\nstates of a semiconductor nanowire weak link with a single dominant\n(spin-degenerate) Andreev level. We found that the microwave susceptibility\ndoes not exhibit a particle-hole symmetry, which we qualitatively explain as an\ninfluence of Coulomb interaction. Moreover, our state-selective measurement\nreveals a large, $\\pi$-phase shifted contribution to the response common to all\nmany-body states which can be interpreted as arising from a phase-dependent\ncontinuum in the superconducting density of states.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 10 Dec 2021 16:00:01 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-11-30"}
